operty)."]}]},{"name":"Swale","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire):","topographic name from the Swale river in North Yorkshire, the name of which probably derives from Old English <i>swalwe</i> ‘whirlpool or rushing water’.","alternatively, perhaps from the Middle English female personal name <i>Swale</i>, Old Norse <i>Svala</i>, from <i>svala</i> ‘swallow’ (the bird)."],"variants":[{"name":"Swales","meanings":["English (North and Yorkshire): variant of   Swale  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert De Swale was born about 1300, in Fremington, Yorkshire, England as the son of Robert Swale and Olina Bolour. He had at least 1 son with Mrs Robert Swale."},"et":{"about 1300–":"umbes 1300–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1325–1390":"1325–1390","–Male":"Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1390":"1390","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Fremington, Yorkshire, England":"Fremington, Yorkshire, England","West Grinton, Yorkshire, England":"Grinton, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1300–":"noin 1300–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1325–1390":"1325–1390","–Male":"Kuollut","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1300":"noin 1300","1390":"1390","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Fremington, Yorkshire, England":"Fremington, Yorkshire, England","West Grinton, Yorkshire, England":"Grinton, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1300–":"environ 1300–Décédé","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1325–1390":"1325–1390","–Male":"Décédé","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1300":"environ 1300","1390":"1390","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Fremington, Yorkshire, England":"Fremington, Everwyck, Angleterre","West Grinton, Yorkshire, England":"Grint